 , a surname of French origin. Compare   Demory  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Damory KNIGHT was born about 1230, in Bucknell, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs-Robert D’Amory. He died about 1285, at the age of 57."},"et":{"about 1230–about 1285":"umbes 1230–umbes 1285","1234–Female":"1234–Surnud","1280–1330":"1280–1330","1284–1321":"1284–1321","1230–1285":"1230–1285","1234":"1234","1321":"1321","1330":"1330","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","Abt 1280":"umbes 1280","1280":"1280","about 1230":"umbes 1230","about 1285":"umbes 1285","Bletchingdon, Oxfordshire, England":"Bletchingdon, Oxfordshire, England","Of, Bucknell, Oxford, England":"Bucknell, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bucknell, Bicester, Oxfordshire, England":"Bucknell, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1230–about 1285":"noin 1230–noin 1285","1234–Female":"1234–Kuollut","1280–1330":"1280–1330","1284–1321":"1284–1321","1230–1285":"1230–1285","1234":"123